{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-publication-index-js","path":"/en/dp/144/myths-and-facts-about-inequalities-in-thailand/","result":{"data":{"meta":{"siteMetadata":{"collections":[{"collection":"abridged","title":"aBRIDGEd","subtitle":"Making Research Accessible","url":"/abridged/","placeholder":null},{"collection":"thaipublica","title":"เศรษฐศาสตร์เข้า \"ท่า\"","subtitle":"Making Research Make Sense","url":"/thaipublica/","placeholder":null},{"collection":"pierspectives","title":"PIERspectives","subtitle":"Making Research Comprehensible","url":"/pierspectives/","placeholder":"pierspectives"},{"collection":"dp","title":"Discussion Paper","subtitle":"Making Research Inaccessible","url":"/dp/","placeholder":"dp"},{"collection":"members","title":"Members","subtitle":"Making Research Possible","url":"/pier-research-network/","placeholder":null},{"collection":"announcements","title":"Announcements","subtitle":"Making Research Public","url":"/announcements/","placeholder":"announcements"},{"collection":"blog","title":"PIER Blog","subtitle":"Making Research Public","url":"/blog/","placeholder":"blog"},{"collection":"conferences","title":"Conferences","subtitle":"Making Research Big","url":"/conferences/","placeholder":"conferences"},{"collection":"workshops","title":"Workshops and Forums","subtitle":"Making Research Work","url":"/workshops/","placeholder":"seminars"},{"collection":"seminars","title":"PIER Economic Seminars","subtitle":"Making Research Better","url":"/seminars/","placeholder":"seminars"},{"collection":"exchange","title":"PIER Research Exchange","subtitle":"Making Research Exchangable","url":"/exchange/","placeholder":"seminars"}],"series":[{"series":"Industry Transformation","placeholder":"industry-transformation"},{"series":"Public Economics","placeholder":"public-economics"}]}},"mdx":{"body":"var _excluded = [\"components\"];\n\nfunction _extends() { _extends = Object.assign || function (target) { for (var i = 1; i < arguments.length; i++) { var source = arguments[i]; for (var key in source) { if (Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(source, key)) { target[key] = source[key]; } } } return target; }; return _extends.apply(this, arguments); }\n\nfunction _objectWithoutProperties(source, excluded) { if (source == null) return {}; var target = _objectWithoutPropertiesLoose(source, excluded); var key, i; if (Object.getOwnPropertySymbols) { var sourceSymbolKeys = Object.getOwnPropertySymbols(source); for (i = 0; i < sourceSymbolKeys.length; i++) { key = sourceSymbolKeys[i]; if (excluded.indexOf(key) >= 0) continue; if (!Object.prototype.propertyIsEnumerable.call(source, key)) continue; target[key] = source[key]; } } return target; }\n\nfunction _objectWithoutPropertiesLoose(source, excluded) { if (source == null) return {}; var target = {}; var sourceKeys = Object.keys(source); var key, i; for (i = 0; i < sourceKeys.length; i++) { key = sourceKeys[i]; if (excluded.indexOf(key) >= 0) continue; target[key] = source[key]; } return target; }\n\n/* @jsxRuntime classic */\n\n/* @jsx mdx */\nvar _frontmatter = {\n  \"id\": \"144\",\n  \"title\": \"Myths and Facts about Inequalities in Thailand\",\n  \"authors\": [\"Nuarpear Lekfuangfu\", \"Suphanit Piyapromdee\", \"Ponpoje Porapakkarm\", \"Nada Wasi\"],\n  \"date\": \"2020-11-27T00:00:00.000Z\",\n  \"pdf\": \"pier_dp_144.pdf\"\n};\nvar layoutProps = {\n  _frontmatter: _frontmatter\n};\nvar MDXLayout = \"wrapper\";\nreturn function MDXContent(_ref) {\n  var components = _ref.components,\n      props = _objectWithoutProperties(_ref, _excluded);\n\n  return mdx(MDXLayout, _extends({}, layoutProps, props, {\n    components: components,\n    mdxType: \"MDXLayout\"\n  }), mdx(\"p\", null, \"This paper analyzes inequalities in Thailand over the past three decades and the implications of Covid-19 on existing inequalities. We show that while total income and consumption inequalities in Thailand have been declining, it raises concerns regarding some drivers behind the declining trends. First, the decline in income inequality among the older households is largely driven by private transfers. Given Thailand\\u2019s demographic transformation into aging society, this channel is not sustainable. Second, despite the increasing longevity trend, household heads aged 55\\u201369 years old have become inactive in the labor markets over the years. Among active households, the earnings inequality among households who mainly earn from farming activities has risen. However, such increase was masked at the aggregate level because of the higher shares of households working in non-farm sectors and the decline in their earnings inequality. Third, while consumption inequality has fallen similarly to income inequality for all age groups, the low-income households remain highly exposed to income shock. These poor households have much higher shares of essential spending, which are harder to adjust. Finally, while the full effects of Covid-19 on inequality are still unfolding, our evidence shows that in the short-run the poor and the low educated are vulnerable to job and earnings losses.\"));\n}\n;\nMDXContent.isMDXComponent = true;","fields":{"slug":"/dp/144/myths-and-facts-about-inequalities-in-thailand/","collection":"dp","shorturl":"/dp/144/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Myths and Facts about Inequalities in Thailand","subtitle":null,"series":null,"authors":["Nuarpear Lekfuangfu","Suphanit Piyapromdee","Ponpoje Porapakkarm","Nada Wasi"],"date":"2020-11-27T00:00:00.000Z","updated":null,"cover":null,"excerpt":null,"bibliography":null,"topics":null,"tags":null,"layout":null,"pdf":{"publicURL":"/static/1a994c61ee2bd2fee9b288576af5c8cc/pier_dp_144.pdf"}},"authors":[{"frontmatter":{"memberid":"Nada Wasi","title":"Nada Wasi","org":"pier","email":"NadaW@bot.or.th","image":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"constrained","backgroundColor":"#f8f8f8","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/4f51bf5a73b60ec87a90942ad354c6da/dd515/profile.jpg","srcSet":"/sta